<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-826-344  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 826 344.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Government Computer News  Sept 3 1990 v9 n18 p107(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Postal Service moves to automate magazine, newspaper processing.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Grimm, Vanessa Jo.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Martin Marietta Corp. (products).andO;Ticker:    ML.andO;Topic:     United States. Postal ServiceAutomationNewspapersMail ProcessingMagazinesEquipment Acquisition.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Postal Service Moves to Automate Magazine, Newspaper ProcessingandM;The Postal Service made moves last month to increase automated processing oflarger flat mail, such as big envelopes, magazines and newspapers.andM;The Board of Governors approved spending $41.4 million for computer-drivenmachines to sort flat mail.andP;  Now mechanized machines, which must be loadedand unloaded manually, process this mail.andM;The new flats sorters will load and remove mail trays semiautomatically.andP;  Themachines can handle a broader range of sizes and weights, too.andM;The service which has been developing the improved equipment with vendorsincluding Martin Marietta Corp., plans to have the machines fully operationalby 1994.andM;The older machines hourly sort 7,000 to 10,000 pieces, each weighing up to 1pound.andP;  The automated flats sorters will be able to sort 21,000 pieces ofmail each hour and can handle pieces weighing as much as 3 pounds.andM;Postal officials said the equipment would exceed the corporate AutomationPlan goal, which mandated that by 1995 the service have an automated flatssorter capable of processing 16,500 pieces of mail an hour.andP;  The plan callsfor all mail to be processed automatically by 1995, using bar codes.andM;Meanwhile, Postal Service finances are looking up, and executives attributedthe change to automation.andP;  Earlier this year, the service estimated it wouldsuffer a net loss of $1.6 billion for fiscal 1990, but Postmaster GeneralAnthony M. Frank now says the agency's deficit will drop below $1 billion.andO;</TEXT></DOC>